<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=dune&Board=shadow&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Dune (dune) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">1. Try HT'ing a mob that's cons even or 2 levels above you. You'll see how much HT is resisted then.<br>
HT is great for taunting. And when it actually is not resisted it does some decent extra damage. But that's when it's not resisted. Have you heard anything from people post 50? At their level HT does 500 some odd points of damage. It seems much when you're level 20, but to them it's laughable. Mobs tend to have 10k+ of hp's. <br>
All HT is: extra damage that actually decreases, in a way, as you go up in levels.<p>

2. Lifetaps? You use life taps? Your sk must be in his teens. Once you reach certain level lifetaps become next to useless. I have about 1000 hps. Try tapping your health back at 45 hps per cast (I'm under level 39. This is the strongest Lifetap you get before then). You'll run out of mana way before you even get 3/4 of a bubble. <br>
In a fight that lifetap will extend your life for maybe 1 or 2 hits. While you're wasting your time lifetapping it you could have done a lot more damage by hitting the mob with your weapon.<br>
At my level mobs hit for 80 hps. Sure I use it too, when I'm in a low level area, I'll tap a rat or some other greene if I'm in need of health. I haven't had Lifetap memorized for quite a while. For life taps to be useful they would have to leach a lot more hps than this. In the 50's sk's get some actual decent lifetaps. But like someone on this board said you have to wait a long time before your sk starts performing satisfactory.<br>
Hmmm, that means just a few more weeks of gaming at 16 hours a day. Sure, no problem. I don't have a life, family, friends. I don't need to sleep or work or eat. I'll spend my entire life playing a game so that eventually I can say: Sure I spend so much time playing it, haven't really accomplished everything, but hey, I spend 10 bucks a month. Rrrriiiigggghhhhtttttt...<p>

3. Great, we get some excellent weapons. Try getting one. You'll have to dig deep in your pocket before you convince anyone to part with one of those. If you want to get one of them by yourself you better have the backing of a fairly large guild and a lot of luck. Also, have you seen my post above? With my skills maxed I still miss a LOT or hit like a newbie, and that's with blue mobs!<p>

We can Gather Shadows. Sweet. But guess what, other classes get Invisibility in one form or another. If not a spell then an item.<br>
Feign Death is great. That one I'll give to you. But you have to have time to cast it. It's not instantaneous. If you're getting mobbed by a few monsters chances are you will not be able to cast it. So it has it's faults. (But then everything does. Playing a god like character would be pointless and would get boring fast.)<br>
Darkness spells used to be great, but recently I've noticed that these spells don't last as long as they used to.  My best darkness spell also gets resisted at about 6 out of 10 casts.<br>
Fear kiting is great as long as you don't attack something with high magic resistance (which at my level is rather difficult to find). Fear also gets resisted quite often and most of the time lasts 1 to 10 seconds. I attacked a blue griffin, about 2 levels below me. I ran out of mana way before doing any decent damage to this bugger.<p>

Pets. I agree they are fine for soloing. In effect they are an low level, long lasting DOT spell. But since they are so much lower than their masters they tend to attract trouble like sh*t attracts flies. The point is they don't need to be much higher but their agrro should be at the same level as their owner. Saying that you have to be careful when using a pet is dumb. All casters have some kind of difficulty controlling their pets. But what they don't have to deal with is green mobs attacking your party because your pet is in the green mobs' aggro range.<p>

What I'd like to see is SK's getting improved. We pay a hefty experience penalty (the highest of all classes) for nothing that really warrants it.<br>
I don't want a god character, but one that actually does what he was meant to do. A nasty, spell casting killer.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
